revision.text:
==English==
===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|yearn}}
===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|yern||willing, eager}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ġeorn||eager}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*gern}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*gernaz}}.
Cognate with {{cog|da|gerne||gladly}}, {{cog|nl|gaarne||with pleasure, gladly}}, {{cog|de|gern||willingly, gladly}}, {{cog|is|gjarn||willing, keen, eager}}, {{cog|is|gjarna||willingly, readily, gladdly}}, {{cog|sv|gärna||willingly, gladly}}. See also [[yearnful]] and [[yearnfully]].
===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/jəːn/}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɜː(ɹ)n|s=1}}
{{homophones|en|yearn}}
===Adverb===
{{head|en|adverb}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[eagerly|eagerly]], [[heartily]], [[gladly]], [[willingly]], [[earnestly]].
#: {{ux|en|I am not afraid of death, and when my time comes I'll go '''yern'''.}}
#* '''1865''', Frederick James Furnivall, ''A Royal Historie of the Excellent Knight Generides''
#*: Who was so hardie and so stern? Tel me now, I pray you '''yern'''
#* '''c. 1515''', unknown ''The Buke of the Sevyne Sagis''
#*: All the people cried '''yern'''ː God Master, now defend thy bairn.
#* '''1513''', {{w|Gavin Douglas}}, ''The Eneados''
#*: The black swarm ower the fields walks '''yerne'''
====Usage notes====
For the adverb, the form {{m|en|yearnly}} can also be found, but is much rarer.
